title: For Sale/Trade:  M1 Carbine - Plainfield Machine - Fired less than 20 rounds, Highly collectible!!!
postcontent:
This is the revered M1 Carbine , "the backup to 'the greatest battle implement ever devised' in WWII" ... caliber .30 Carbine.  It is a Plainfield Machine version which is highly collectible yet still reasonably priced (versus the one or two most collectible versions which sell for a thousand or two easy when they're posted, and the best condition examples either don't get posted for sale or get so much money you can't even think about them).

This was made by Plainfield Machine Co. in the mid 1970s (most likely).  It was purchased by my Father as a young police officer in New Jersey, off the rack in K-Mart.  One of his fellow officers told him he could get an amazing deal on a high-quality, historical rifle at the local K-Mart and he happened to get one as they were being delivered... He claims to have fired it a few times in the 1970s, put it away... took it out once when I was a young child in the mid to late 1980s, and then once more in the time leading up to the AWB of 1994.  It then went into storage and has not been fired since, to the best of our knowledge.  We are not even sure if it has been fired a full box of ammo... if so, we are talking minimal shooting here.  My Dad is not and I repeat NOT a gun guy, to him they were just tools of the trade for work, and he surely wasn't a rifle guy by any stretch of the imagination.... When he was issued a new semiautomatic 9mm Glock in the 80s that was his gun, and it was good enough for him.

So this is for sale because it is of little use to me , and little historical value.  It's not like it was a family heirloom piece or he used it on some special mission or in some special times, not at all.  To be honest when he was telling me about it, I thought it was an M1A and I was so excited to have a possible M1A in storage, my heart was secretly broken when I realized he wasn't accurate in his descriptions and it was an M1 Carbine lol.

It is in excellent condition, probably needs a thorough cleaning and lubrication before any use but other than  that, should make an EXCELLENT ranch rifle or personal protection piece of firearms history.  It's nice enough to be a collection piece in addition to a user-shooting gun but functionable enough to be a shooter, not a safe queen.

$800 gets it done

FINAL NOTE- The Manufacturer is Plainfield Machine of Dunellen, NJ - This was a very well known and boutique-style arms-making factory that was acquired by Iver Johnson I believe in 1978?  I am pretty sure through serial number research that this was either made right before the aquisition/merger or perhaps right after and before the machine tooling was changed to a new stamp etc.  The rifle reads Plainfield Machine Dunellen NJ .30 M1 and has a 5-digit serial number in the 60,000 - 's.  A piece of history that could be cherished and used.  -- I did some research, and apparently the Plainfield Machine carbines that feature the Dunellen NJ markings are the best that Plainfield produced- they are Plainfield-made receivers with Plainfield-made barrels, and then all USGI parts.  They also have some of the best stocks you'll find under $1000 models.  Several sources online refer to Plainfield Machine Dunellen-models as the best M1 Carbine you can buy if you are at all interested in shooting, as they are head and shoulders better than anything under them and the models above them are either extremely expensive or just too nice/valuable/pristine to shoot .  This is a perfect combination of function and features so the collector/shooter loves them.

You will not be disappointed with these sights.  They glow nice and bright and are priced less than anywhere else you will find.

location: St. Cloud or NW suburbs, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent:
When I bought this it looked to be brand new. I only put 2 rounds of Hornady Leverevolution through it, then cleaned it and put it into the safe. I've since decided to replace it with a Savage 220, since a slug gun serves multiple needs.

It has an 18.5" unported barrel. I also added scope mounts, but no scope (the open sights can still be used with the mounts on). I have the original box containing the offset hammer spur, screws that were removed to install the scope mounts and the original paperwork.

It has a Marlin serial number of 91xxxxxx (Remington numbers started with MR), which means it was made in 2009. It still says New Haven, Ct on the barrel but has a REP stamp. The receiver looks to be a Marlin part, but the serial number is in the Remington location. My research indicated that this one was probably built in Ilion, NY with mostly Marlin parts. It looks and works as well as an older Marlin guide gun that I had, unlike some that I've heard about.

I have the remaining 18 rounds of Hornady ammo that will go with it for a full price offer.

I'm looking for a local sale/trade only. If the ad's still here it's still for sale.
